# Remote Hardware Monitoring & Control App

> Real-time IoT hardware monitoring and remote control via MQTT on Android.

![Platform](https://img.shields.io/badge/Platform-Android-3DDC84?style=flat&logo=android&logoColor=white)
![Language](https://img.shields.io/badge/Language-Kotlin-7F52FF?style=flat&logo=kotlin&logoColor=white)
![Protocol](https://img.shields.io/badge/Protocol-MQTT-660066?style=flat)
![Status](https://img.shields.io/badge/Status-Production-brightgreen?style=flat)

## Overview

An Android IoT application that enables engineers to monitor live sensor data and remotely control hardware devices — all from their phone. Built to handle continuous data streams reliably without draining the battery.

## Key Features

- **Real-time monitoring** — Live hardware data via MQTT with near-zero latency
- **Remote control** — Send commands to connected hardware devices from anywhere
- **Always-on streaming** — Foreground service ensures continuous data flow with no interruptions
- **Battery optimised** — Background execution tuned to reduce battery consumption by ~30% vs naive approach
- **Auto-reconnect** — Automatic MQTT reconnection on network loss with no data gaps

## Tech Stack

| Layer | Technology |
|---|---|
| Language | Kotlin |
| Protocol | MQTT (Eclipse Paho) |
| Architecture | MVVM |
| Background | Android Foreground Services |
| Build | Gradle, Android SDK |

## Architecture

```
UI Layer (Activities/Fragments)
       │
ViewModel (MVVM)
       │
Repository
       │
MQTT Service (Foreground) ←→ Hardware Devices
```

## Getting Started

1. Clone the repo
   ```bash
   git clone https://github.com/Areesha555/<repo-name>.git
   ```
2. Open in Android Studio
3. Configure your MQTT broker address in `MqttConfig.kt`
4. Build and run on a physical Android device (API 26+)

